    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-09-13T14:45:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-09-13T14:45:00-05:00" n="845"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d845">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">817.00 <persName corresp="#p_WRACH1"
                        >Woodward</persName> Electoral Mission/161: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_HME1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hanna</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-09-13T14:00:00-05:45"
                            >September 13, 1932—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 4:34 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>175. Conditions along the Managua–Matagalpa road make an armed escort necessary
                    for supplies sent from here to Matagalpa for the personnel of the Electoral
                    Mission there and protective detachment of marines—a total of approximately 50
                    marines. <persName corresp="#p_MMGCB1">General Matthews</persName> states that
                    this escort cannot be furnished by the Guardia at this time and consequently
                    must be furnished by marines. From information given me by General <persName
                        corresp="#p_BRC1">Berkeley</persName> it seems that the Navy Department is
                    withholding its approval of the employment of marines <pb facs="0927" n="823"
                        xml:id="pg_823"/> for this purpose on the ground that the State Department
                    may object. The Navy Department doubtless will consult you in this connection. I
                    concur in General <persName corresp="#p_BRC1">Berkeley</persName>’s and
                        <persName corresp="#p_MMGCB1">General Matthews</persName>’ views that the
                    marines escort is necessary. The matter is urgent.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HME1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hanna</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
